image_info: Toxocara sp. egg teased from an adult worm. The worm was never identified, but the egg size is most consistent with T. cati. Image courtesy of the New Jersey State Public Health Laboratory.
Toxocara sp. egg teased from an adult worm. The worm was never identified, but the egg size is most consistent with T. cati. Image courtesy of the New Jersey State Public Health Laboratory.
Toxocara sp. egg at 400× magnification, approximately 75 µm.
Toxocara canis larva beginning to hatch.
Toxocara canis adult male and female.
Close-up of the anterior end of Toxocara canis, showing the three lips characteristic of ascarid worms. Image courtesy of the New Jersey State Public Health Laboratory.
Close-up of the anterior end of Toxocara cati, showing the three lips characteristic of ascarid worms.
Side view of Image C, showing the broad alae with striations, characteristic of T. cati.
Close-up of the posterior end of T. cati, showing a prominent digitiform point at the posterior extremity.
Close-up of the posterior end of Toxocara sp. Image courtesy of the New Jersey State Public Health Laboratories.
Cross-section of Toxocara sp. larvae in liver tissue stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E).
Longitudinal section of a Toxocara sp. larva in liver tissue stained with H&E.
Longitudinal section of a Toxocara sp. larva in lung tissue stained with H&E.
Figure D. Toxocara canis longitudinal section (arrow) in the liver of an infected monkey. Note the prominent granulomatous reaction and host infiltrate around the larva (20x magnification).
Cross-section of a larva of T. cati, showing prominent lateral alae (arrows). Diameter is 15 µm.
